[[Image:After an Entomological Sale by Edward Armitage, 1878.jpg|thumb|230px|The sale of Edwin Brown's insect collection]] '''Edwin Brown''' (died 1 September 1876, [[Tenby]]) was an [[England|English]] [[naturalist]] and [[entomologist]].
Edwin Brown was manager of the Burton, Uttoxeter and Ashbourne Union Bank in [[Burton on Trent]]. He had a private museum of geological, zoological and botanical specimens and a library of taxonomic works.<ref>[http://www.darwinproject.ac.uk/letter/entry-3771 Bates to Charles Darwin letter], www.darwinproject.ac.uk</ref> <ref>Anon Obit. ''[[Entomologist's Monthly Magazine]]'' 13 (1876–7):116 [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35879#page/146/mode/2up online]</ref> Brown was a Member of the [[Royal Entomological Society|Entomological Society of London]] from 1849. He specialised in [[Carabidae]] and [[Cicindelidae]].<ref>Adrian Brown Memorial Lecture. ''Journal of the Institute of Brewing'' Volume 27, Issue 5 doi= 10.1002/j.2050-0416.1921.tb02482.x</ref>
Parts of his collection were purchased by [[Oxford University Museum of Natural History]] when it was sold at auction in March 1877. The purchase included insects collected by [[Alfred Russel Wallace]].
Edwin Brown was [[Henry Walter Bates]]'s first [[naturalist]] friend.<ref>Frederick Burkhardt and Sydney Smith, 1994 ''A Calendar of the Correspondence of Charles Darwin, 1821–1882'' Cambridge University Press {{ISBN|9780521434232}}</ref>
==Works== Partial list *Contributions to [[Sir Oswald Mosley, 2nd Baronet, of Ancoats|Mosley, O.]] ''Natural History of Tutbury''(1863) *On the Australian species of Tetracha. ''Transactions of The Royal Entomological Society of London'' 17: 351-353 (1869)
