{{short description|An international multidisciplinary project that studied deep-sea ecosystems along Europe's deep-ocean margin}}
'''Hotspot Ecosystems Research on the Margins of European Seas''', or '''HERMES''', was an international multidisciplinary project, from April 2005 to March 2009, that studied deep-sea [[ecosystems]] along Europe's deep-ocean margin.<ref name=hermes>[http://www.eu-hermes.net/ '''HERMES''' website, http://www.eu-hermes.net/]</ref><ref name=weaver1>Weaver, P.P.E., and Gunn, V. (2009). [http://www.tos.org/oceanography/issues/issue_archive/issue_pdfs/22_1/22-1_weaver_intro.pdf "HERMES: Hotspot Ecosystem Research on the Margins of European Seas".] ''Oceanography'' 22 (1), March 2009.</ref><ref name=grehan1>Grehan et al (2009). [http://www.tos.org/oceanography/issues/issue_archive/issue_pdfs/22_1/22-1_grehan.pdf "HERMES: Promoting Ecosystem-Based Management and the Sustainable Use and Governance of Deep-Water Resources".] ''Oceanography'' 22 (1), March 2009.</ref>

The HERMES project was funded by the [[European Commission]]'s [[Sixth Framework Programme]], and was the predecessor to the [[HERMIONE project]], which started in April 2009.<ref name=hermione>[http://www.eu-hermione.net/ '''HERMIONE''' website, http://www.eu-hermione.net/]</ref>

