{{Redirect|Lunar gardening|lunar gardening based on moon phases|Agricultural astrology}}
'''Impact gardening''' is the process by which [[impact event]]s stir the outermost [[crust (geology)|crust]]s of moons and other celestial objects with no [[atmosphere]]s. In the particular case of the [[Moon]], this is more often known as '''lunar gardening'''.  Planetary bodies lacking an atmosphere will generally also lack any [[erosion]]al processes, with the possible exception of [[volcanism]], and as a result impact debris accumulates at the object's surface as a rough "soil," commonly referred to as [[regolith]]. Subsequent impacts, especially by [[micrometeorite]]s, stir and mix this soil. It had long been estimated that the top centimeter of the lunar surface is overturned every 10 million years.<ref>{{cite book|first1=George H. A. |last1=Cole |first2=Michael Mark |last2=Woolfson |author-link2=Michael Woolfson |title=Planetary Science: The Science of Planets Around Stars |page=96 |date=2002 |publisher=[[CRC Press]] }}</ref> However more recent analysis by the [[Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter|LRO satellite]], of impact ejecta coverage, puts the figure closer to 80,000 years.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Emerson J. |last1=Speyerer |first2=Reinhold Z. |last2=Povilaitis |first3=Mark S. |last3=Robinson |first4=Peter C. |last4=Thomas |first5=Robert V. |last5=Wagner |journal=Nature |volume=538 |pages=215–218 |date=13 October 2016 |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v538/n7624/full/nature19829.html |title=Quantifying crater production and regolith overturn on the Moon with temporal imaging |doi=10.1038/nature19829 }}</ref>

