'''Khālid ibn ʿAbd al‐Malik al‐Marwarrūdhī''' ({{lang-ar|خالد بن عبدالملك}}) was a [[Zanj]]i slave who was taken to Persia in  the 9th century.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}

Together with [[ʿAlī ibn ʿĪsā al-Asṭurlābī]] in 827, he measured at [[35th parallel north|35 degrees north]] [[latitude]], in the valley of the [[Tigris]], the [[length]] of a [[meridian arc]] and thus the [[Earth]]'s [[circumference]], getting a result of 40,248&nbsp;km (or, according to other sources, 41,436&nbsp;km). The two researchers measured in Arabian [[ell]], and determined the geographical latitudes of the end points they used from the [[altitude|star altitudes]] in a celestial [[horizontal coordinate system]]. We believe that 1 Arabian ell was 49 1/3&nbsp;cm. Thus, they found the length of 1° of meridian to be 111.8&nbsp;km (115.1&nbsp;km), which differs from the actual value by 850 metres.

