'''Natural deep eutectic solvents''' ('''NADES''') are bio-based [[ionic liquid]]s and [[Deep eutectic solvent|deep eutectic solvents]] which are composed of two or more compounds that are generally plant based [[Primary metabolite|primary metabolites]], i.e. [[Organic acid|organic acids]], [[Sugar|sugars]], [[Alcohol|alcohols]], [[Amine|amines]] and [[Amino acid|amino acids]].<ref name=choi>{{Cite journal|author1=Choi, Young Hae |author2=van Spronsen, Jaap |author3=Yuntao, Dai |author4=Verberne, Marianne |author5=Hollmann, Frank |author6=Arends, Isabel W.C.E. |author-link6=Isabel Arends |author7=Witkamp, Geert-Jan |author8=Verpoorte, Rob | year = 2011| title = Are Natural Deep Eutectic Solvents the Missing Link in Understanding Cellular Metabolism and Physiology| journal = Plant Physiology | pages = 1701–1705| doi =  10.1104/pp.111.178426| volume=156 |issue=4 | pmid=21677097 | pmc=3149944}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Dai, Yuntao |author2=van Spronsen, Jaap |author3=Witkamp, Geert-Jan |author4=Verpoorte, Rob |author5=Choi, Young Hae | year = 2013| title = Natural deep eutectic solvents as new potential media for green technology| journal = Analytica Chimica Acta | volume = 766| pages = 61–68|doi=10.1016/j.aca.2012.12.019 | pmid = 23427801}}</ref>  Ionic liquids are [[Salt (chemistry)|salts]], liquid at room temperature, characterized by [[Ionic bonding|ionic bonds]] which have at least one large organic [[ion]] and a cation with a low degree of symmetry.  The positive and negatively charged ions in the liquid are thus kept far apart so that they reduce the attractive forces between them and hinder [[crystallization]], lowering the [[melting point]] and resulting in a completely ionic liquid at room temperature.<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Earle, Martyn J. |author2=Seddon, Kenneth R. | year = 2000| title = Ionic liquids. Green solvents for the future| journal = Pure and Applied Chemistry | pages = 1391–1398 | doi=10.1351/pac200072071391}}</ref>  Deep eutectic solvents (DES) are mixtures of solid compounds that form liquids due to a large depression of the melting point; the charge delocalization in the case of DES is caused by [[hydrogen bond]]ing forming a non-aqueous liquid at room temperature.<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Abbott, Andrew P. |author2=Boothby, David |author3=Capper, Glen |author4=Davies, David L. |author5=Rasheed, Raymond K. | year = 2004| title = Deep Eutectic Solvents Formed between Choline Chloride and Carboxylic acids: Versatile Alternatives to Ionic Liquids| journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society |volume=126 |issue=29 | pages = 9142–9147|doi=10.1021/ja048266j }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Dai, Yuntao |author2=van Spronsen, Jaap |author3=Witkamp, Geert-Jan |author4=Verpoorte, Robert |author5=Choi, Young Hae | year = 2013| title = Ionic Liquids and Deep Eutectic Solvents in Natural Products Research: Mixtures of Solids as Extraction Solvents| journal = Journal of Natural Products | volume = 76| issue = 11| pages = 2162–2173|doi=10.1021/np400051w | pmid = 24188074|pmc=3841005}}</ref>  Work done by Choi, Spronsen ''et al''.<ref name=choi /> showed that water can be present as part of the [[solvent]], being strongly retained in the liquid and which cannot be [[Evaporation|evaporated]].

